krieg_panel3_myeloid_DS02

Yen Hoang

14 June 2018

Re-analyze Krieg data with PRIanalyzer

This is bla bla. We think with our approach we might get better insights from this data set. Descriptive statistics based on doi: 10.12688/f1000research.11622.2

Data description

CyTOF data

Total samples n=60 were distributed over 2 datasets. 20 melanoma patients before (R=11 and NR=9) and after (12 weeks treatment) treatment initiation and 10 healthy controls using metal-labeled antibodies.

Figure 1: CyTOF Dataset overview

Figure 2: CyTOF Staining Panel 3

With our Upload-tool, data is already asinh-transformed with function asinh().

Preprocession DS02

Manipulate data (transformation)

### long version to manipulate data and then merge
if (FALSE) {
  this=fcs
  
  library(reshape2)
  
  shortnames = sub("_CD14CD16.fcs$","",metadata$file_name)
  shortnames = sub("^FCS_","",shortnames)
  data.gated.all = data.trimmed.all = data.man.all = data.frame()
  
  for ( i in 1:length(metadata$file_name) ) {
    #i=1
    ### file index in database
    db_index = which(this$current.filenames==metadata$file_name[i])
    
    ### get marker names and data
    this$selected.vars = this$getVariables(table=this$current.project,index=db_index)
    data.gated = this$getData(table=this$current.project,fileidx=db_index)
    
    ### Remove non-functional parameters
    idx.nonfunvar = grep("FSC|SSC|Time",colnames(data.gated))
    if (length(idx.nonfunvar)>0) data.gated = data.gated[,-idx.nonfunvar]
    
    ### manipulate data part #1
    file_ids = rep(i, nrow(data.gated))
    data.man = data.frame(file_id = file_ids, data.gated)
    
    ### concenate data.gated into one matrix: data.gated.all
    # generate sample IDs corresponding to each cell in the 'data' matrix
    col.fileid = rep(metadata$file_name[i],nrow(data.gated))
    data.gated = cbind(file_id=col.fileid,data.gated)
    if ( i==1 ) {
      data.gated.all = data.gated
    }  else {
      data.gated.all <- merge(data.gated.all,data.gated,all=T)
    }
    
    ### Save gated data
    save(data.gated, file = sprintf("KRIEG/%s_gated.rda",shortnames[i]))
    
    ### trim data.gated for outliers
    ### NOTE: no need since data is gated
    if (FALSE) {
      data.trimmed = data.gated
      cells.removed = 0
      for (t in 1:ncol(data.trimmed)) {
        data.trimmed = data.trimmed[order(data.trimmed[,t]),]
        trim = floor(nrow(data.trimmed)*0.998)
        cells.removed = cells.removed + 2*(nrow(data.trimmed)-trim) -1
        data.trimmed = data.trimmed[(nrow(data.trimmed)-trim):trim,]
      }
      printf("Cells trimmed: -%s cells", cells.removed)
      
      ### Save trimmed data as rdata
      save(data.trimmed, file = sprintf("KRIEG/%s_trimmed.rda",shortnames[i]))
      ### concenate data.trimmed into one matrix: data.trimmed.all
      if ( i==1 ) {
        data.trimmed.all = data.trimmed
      }  else {
        data.trimmed.all <- merge(data.trimmed.all,data.trimmed,all=T)
      }
    }
    
    ### manipulate data part #2
    data.man = melt(data.man, id.var = "file_id", value.name = "expression", variable.name = "marker")
    #head(data.man,2)
    matchmeta = match(data.man$file_id, metadata$file_id)
    data.man$condition = metadata$condition[matchmeta]
    #head(data.man,2)
    ### Save manipulated data as rdata
    save(data.man, file = sprintf("KRIEG/%s_manipulated.rda",shortnames[i]))
    
    ### concenate data.man into one matrix: data.man.all
    if ( i==1 ) {
      data.man.all = data.man
    }  else {
      data.man.all <- merge(data.man.all,data.man,all=T)
    }
  }
  print("Done loading, trimming and manipulating data.")
  dim(data.gated.all)
  #[1] 102957    31
  ### Save gated data as rdata
  save(data.gated.all, file = sprintf("KRIEG/%s_ALLDATA_gated.rda",this$current.project))
  
  #dim(data.trimmed.all)
  #[1] 27606    31
  ### Save trimmed data as rdata
  #save(data.trimmed.all, file = sprintf("KRIEG/%s_ALLDATA_trimmed.rda",this$current.project))
  
  dim(data.man.all)
  #[1] 3088710      4
  save(data.man.all, file = sprintf("KRIEG/%s_ALLDATA_manipulated.rda",this$current.project))
}

Marker ranking based on the non-redundancy score (NRS) in DataSet02

library(reshape2)
### short version to load exprs data and then merge
load(file=sprintf("KRIEG/%s_ALLDATA_gated.rda",this$current.project))
#dim(data.gated.all)
#[1] 31156    31
## Define a function that calculates the NRS per sample
NRS <- function(x, ncomp = 3){
  pr <- prcomp(x, center = TRUE, scale. = FALSE)
  score <- rowSums(outer(rep(1, ncol(x)),
  pr$sdev[1:ncomp]^2) * abs(pr$rotation[,1:ncomp]))
  
  return(score)
}
## Calculate the score
data.NRS = list()
for ( i in 1:length(metadata$file_id) ) {
  data.tmp = data.gated.all[which(data.gated.all[,1]==metadata$file_name[i]),(2:ncol(data.gated.all))]
  data.NRS[[i]] = NRS(data.tmp)
}
data.nrs = t(as.data.frame((data.NRS)))
rownames(data.nrs) = metadata$sample_id
nrs.mean = colMeans(data.nrs)
## Plot the NRS for ordered markers
nrs.sorted = names(sort(nrs.mean, decreasing = TRUE))
data.nrs = data.frame(data.nrs)
data.nrs$sample_id = rownames(data.nrs)
colnames(data.nrs) = c(colnames(data.tmp),"sample_id")
ggdf.nrs = melt(data.nrs, id.var = "sample_id",
                value.name = "nrs", variable.name = "marker")
ggdf.nrs$marker = factor(ggdf.nrs$marker, levels=nrs.sorted)
matchmeta = match(ggdf.nrs$sample_id, metadata$sample_id)
ggdf.nrs$condition <- metadata$condition[matchmeta]
ggplot(ggdf.nrs, aes(x = marker, y = nrs)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = condition), alpha = 0.9,
             position = position_jitter(width = 0.3, height = 0)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.color = NA, fill = NA) +
  stat_summary(fun.y = "mean", geom = "point", shape = 21, fill = "white") +
  theme_bw() +
  theme( text = element_text(size=12), 
         axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust = 1, size=11)) +
  scale_color_manual(values = color_conditions)

[Figure 7. Non-redundancy scores for each of the 30 markers and all samples in the myeloid dataset. The full points represent the per-sample NR scores (colored by experimental conditions), while empty black circles indicate the mean NR scores from all the samples.
